You can customize the look and feel of your Highcharts graph by altering the options provided during the chart's creation. To change the color of lines and other elements, you can directly set the colors in the `Highcharts.chart()` options. Here's how to modify your existing code to make the lines white:

1. Set the color of the line series to white (`'#FFFFFF'`):

```javascript
series: [{
    name: 'Requests',
    data: [],
    color: '#FFFFFF', // Sets the series line color to white
}]
```

2. If you also want to change the color of the text and the gridlines to white (or a lighter color for better contrast against a gray background), you can update the `yAxis` and `xAxis` properties:

```javascript
xAxis: {
    type: 'datetime',
    tickPixelInterval: 150,
    labels: {
        style: {
            color: '#FFFFFF' // Changes the color of xAxis labels to white
        }
    },
    lineColor: '#FFFFFF', // Changes the color of xAxis line to white
    tickColor: '#FFFFFF' // Changes the color of xAxis ticks to white
},

yAxis: {
    title: {
        text: 'Requests/second',
        style: {
            color: '#FFFFFF' // Changes the color of yAxis title to white
        }
    },
    labels: {
        style: {
            color: '#FFFFFF' // Changes the color of yAxis labels to white
        }
    },
    gridLineColor: '#FFFFFF' // Changes the color of yAxis grid lines to white
},
```

3. For completeness, let's also change the title color:

```javascript
title: {
    text: 'L7 DSTAT ~ http://127.0.0.1:5000/hit',
    style: {
        color: '#FFFFFF' // Changes the color of chart title to white
    }
},
```

By making all the above modifications, the relevant sections of your code will look like this:

```javascript
// Create the Highcharts graph
var chart = Highcharts.chart('requestCountGraph', {
    chart: {
        type: 'line',
        backgroundColor: null,
        events: {
            load: requestDataUpdate
        }
    },
    title: {
        text: 'L7 DSTAT ~ http://127.0.0.1:5000/hit',
        style: {
            color: '#FFFFFF'
        }
    },
    xAxis: {
        type: 'datetime',
        tickPixelInterval: 150,
        labels: {
            style: {
                color: '#FFFFFF'
            }
        },
        lineColor: '#FFFFFF',
        tickColor: '#FFFFFF'
    },
    yAxis: {
        title: {
            text: 'Requests/second',
            style: {
                color: '#FFFFFF'
            }
        },
        labels: {
            style: {
                color: '#FFFFFF'
            }
        },
        gridLineColor: '#FFFFFF'
    },
    plotOptions: {
        line: {
            lineWidth: 2,
        }
    },
    series: [{
        name: 'Requests',
        data: [],
        color: '#FFFFFF'
    }]
});
```

After adding these changes, the lines, text, and gridlines in your Highcharts graph should all be white, which will provide better contrast against a gray background.

Apologies for any confusion—the line should not disappear when you only change the color. However, it's possible that the line's color now matches the background, or there could be another issue affecting the visibility of the line.

To ensure that the line is visible, let's try the following steps to troubleshoot and make the line explicitly white:

1. Verify that the color code `'#FFFFFF'` is correct and not blending with the background. This color code represents white, and if your background is also white or very light, the line will not be visible. If your background is indeed gray, as mentioned in your original message, the white line should be visible.

2. If the line series color is being set to white successfully but you still can't see it, it might be that the line width is too thin or there's an issue with the rendering of the line. Try increasing the line width to see if that makes the line more visible:

```javascript
plotOptions: {
    line: {
        lineWidth: 3, // Increase this to make the line thicker
    }
},
```

3. Double-check if there are any console errors in your browser’s developer tools (usually accessible with F12 or right-click -> Inspect -> Console tab). Errors can help identify if there's something else going wrong with your script or the Highcharts library.

4. Make sure the `color` property is placed inside the `line` object within `plotOptions` if you're trying to customize the line itself:

```javascript
plotOptions: {
    line: {
        lineWidth: 3,
        color: '#FFFFFF', // Line color should be set here if you're customizing within plotOptions
    }
},
```

However, since you want to target the line in a specific series, the color should indeed be set inside the series array as in your original modification:

```javascript
series: [{
    name: 'Requests',
    data: [],
    color: '#FFFFFF', // Make sure this color is different from the background
}]
```

5. If after applying all the changes, you still can't see the line, try hard refresh your web page (`Ctrl + F5` on most browsers) to clear cache and ensure all changes are loaded.

6. If none of the above solutions works, it might be helpful to directly inspect the SVG elements rendered by Highcharts in the browser developer tools. Highcharts creates the graph using SVG, and you may directly select and inspect these elements to make sure they have the correct styles applied.

Add these changes one by one and see which step makes the line visible again. If you're still having trouble, there might be another part of the script that's causing the issue, and we’d need to troubleshoot further.
